snippet.textDisplay:
Enjoy your channel and the new haircut. I’m retired from the US foreign service serving eleven years in Manila between 1983 and 2001 and visiting HK, Macau, Japan, Thailand, Burma, Korea and Indonesia on TDY but never making it to Mainland China. Like you I explored the places the tourist didn’t go an tried to shop like a local ex-pat.

The mention of Dum Sum reminded me of a memorable experience in Hong Kong which came after several days with local guy from the US Consulate there who went with me to translate when looking for an ink supplier my USIA printing plant in Manila. On the final day for lunch I said “Take me somewhere I won’t see another white guy”. Took a cab to a second floor Dum Sum place that was about 10 meters wide but about 60 meters long. It was my introduction to Dim Sum. He asked if there was anything I didn’t like and I replied I was game to try anything... and we did.

The consulate guy also taught me to notice recognize how affluent a person there way based on the style of Rolex they wear: salaryman-stainless, middle manager-stainless+gold, senior manager-solid gold. Business owner? Their Rolex looks at first glance like the stainless salaryman style but in solid Platinum that only a very savvy watch fancier would notice.

A co-worker knowing I was going to HK asked me to bring his calculator with a busted LCD display there to get fixed. In the states we’d throw it away and get a new one. There I found a Casio repair shop walking distance from the Star Ferry and they said, “You come back in two hours...”

Hong Kong also where I learned to haggle with a hand held calculator in camera shops to get past the “insult” price given to foreigners. In a crowed shop they don’t want other customers to here the discount someone else is getting. The only Chinese I learned was “Gay do chin?” Which I hope means “How much?”

I’ve got similar memories from all the other countries I visited in Asia. It is an amazing place especially if you get away from the tourist places and try to interact with the locals. In the Philippines I would take 50 - 100 mile round trip solo mountain bike rides to see the countryside south of Manila on weekends eating at food stalls that probably never had an American customer. I got called “Joe” a lot in the 80s. Buy the late 90s it was “Hey Man...”

I never learned much Taglog grammar because my staff spoke English all the time and at parties if someone asked if I spoke Taglog I would reply “Kanti Lang...” (Just a little) with a really good accent. Then the conversation would resume in English.
